WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:19.940 --> 00:21.965
Oh, hey, can we help you?

00:22.142 --> 00:25.270
- Yeah, we're looking for Private Connellan.
MIKE: Kyle?

00:25.445 --> 00:27.572
I think he's in the lab across the way.

00:28.181 --> 00:29.375
Okay.

00:29.750 --> 00:32.878
I'm always telling him it's not polite
to point with that thing.

00:33.353 --> 00:34.377
Thanks, guys.

00:34.554 --> 00:35.885
TIM:
You're welcome.

00:37.958 --> 00:39.721
Sawyer. Come on.

00:39.893 --> 00:43.385
Oh, hey, does Kyle know you're coming?

00:47.501 --> 00:48.866
[GRUNTS]

00:49.436 --> 00:52.997
They didn't machine the darn thing
the way I asked them to.

00:53.407 --> 00:58.674
It's not like I'm trying to send a man
to the moon, for heaven's sake. Unh.

01:00.781 --> 01:01.975
[DOOR CLOSES]

01:04.785 --> 01:06.980
Well, come on in. Don't just stand there.

01:11.158 --> 01:14.218
I'm Cameron McCarthy. And you are?

01:14.461 --> 01:16.861
I'm Lorraine, Kyle's aunt.

01:17.564 --> 01:19.054
Hi.

01:19.232 --> 01:21.166
And this is Sawyer, his cousin.

01:21.334 --> 01:23.131
Family. Very healing.

01:23.303 --> 01:24.998
Or so I'm told.

01:25.172 --> 01:27.436
Mine always makes me
wanna sharpen the cutlery.

01:28.308 --> 01:30.742
God does quality work, doesn't he?

01:31.178 --> 01:33.442
I'm not sure I can beat that. Hold on.

01:33.613 --> 01:35.308
Let me see.

01:36.216 --> 01:38.514
That's a left foot, a right foot and...
Oh, oh.

01:38.852 --> 01:40.444
Here's the beauty.

01:40.620 --> 01:42.144
- High five.
- Ha, ha.

01:42.322 --> 01:45.519
- Ha-ha-ha.
- Please leave.

01:49.629 --> 01:51.597
We just wanna make sure
you're okay, Kyle.

01:51.765 --> 01:54.359
Well, I'm not, all right?

01:55.869 --> 02:00.363
Shrink is down the hall.
I don't do heads, I do bodies.

02:00.540 --> 02:03.532
So I'm gonna let you all do <i>Jerry Springer</i>
without me.

02:03.710 --> 02:06.406
Kyle, we'll finish this up later on, okay?

02:06.613 --> 02:10.139
Chili burger.
Best American invention since jazz.

02:12.452 --> 02:13.680
KYLE:
Look...

02:14.621 --> 02:17.351
...I didn't ask you to come see me.

02:20.293 --> 02:23.660
Now you saw me, so just please leave.

02:28.001 --> 02:29.332
Fine.

02:29.503 --> 02:31.095
You know, whatever.

02:32.005 --> 02:35.270
Did you ever think that this might be
hard for other people?

02:35.442 --> 02:37.205
People besides you?

02:38.011 --> 02:39.535
Did you?

02:46.454 --> 02:47.853
[DOOR OPENS THEN SLAMS]

02:53.461 --> 02:55.861
What do you say we get an ice cream.

02:56.797 --> 02:58.287
KYLE:
Sawyer.

03:01.435 --> 03:03.528
I'll wait for you in the car.

03:21.088 --> 03:24.057
Look, it's not you.

03:24.392 --> 03:25.689
Okay?

03:26.861 --> 03:28.294
I just need some time.

03:28.896 --> 03:32.297
Yeah, Mom said that your back was hurt.

03:32.833 --> 03:35.199
That you can't move your legs
or something?

03:35.770 --> 03:40.230
Yeah, I mean, my left leg,
it's coming back.

03:40.441 --> 03:43.308
But it's my right side
they're worried about.

03:45.012 --> 03:46.639
Will you be able to walk again?

03:47.715 --> 03:49.342
With a brace...

03:49.517 --> 03:50.950
...maybe.

03:54.655 --> 03:55.917
What about swimming?

03:57.858 --> 04:00.622
Just tell my mom and dad
I'm doing okay.

04:08.769 --> 04:11.237
[MEN YELLING]

04:30.257 --> 04:31.986
Excuse me?

04:32.927 --> 04:33.951
Hi.

04:34.562 --> 04:37.258
Can I ask you a weird question?

04:40.067 --> 04:43.366
All right, I'm looking and I'm listening.

04:43.537 --> 04:44.629
I understand.

04:44.805 --> 04:46.295
No promises.

04:46.974 --> 04:50.205
Hey, Dr. Clay. This is Dr. McCarthy.

04:50.377 --> 04:52.436
- Oh, hi, doctor.
- Hi.

04:52.613 --> 04:53.978
What can I do for you?

04:55.349 --> 04:58.978
Well, I was under the impression
I was here to do something for you.

05:01.188 --> 05:03.179
I was afraid you'd say no.

05:07.695 --> 05:10.129
All right. Let's see here.

05:17.304 --> 05:18.635
[CLICKING]

05:23.844 --> 05:25.311
Right.

05:26.847 --> 05:30.248
Well, to begin with,
she's as smooth as wet silk.

05:30.417 --> 05:33.875
But how would you keep the daggone thing
on her when there's nothing there?

05:34.054 --> 05:35.988
There's nothing to attach anything to.

05:36.156 --> 05:39.887
It's preposterous anyway,
trying to put a tail on a fish.

05:41.395 --> 05:43.955
And nobody in his right mind
would even try.

05:46.700 --> 05:48.133
Luckily...

05:48.869 --> 05:50.166
...I'm not.

05:52.106 --> 05:53.164
Not what?

05:54.241 --> 05:55.902
In my right mind.

05:56.076 --> 05:57.168
CLAY:
So, what does that mean?

05:57.344 --> 05:59.676
You're gonna...? You're gonna try?

06:00.481 --> 06:02.005
McCARTHY:
Well, ahem...

06:03.484 --> 06:06.453
I've got some vacation time coming up.

06:06.921 --> 06:08.582
But I'm not making any promises.

06:09.890 --> 06:11.448
Dr. McCarthy.

06:12.960 --> 06:14.689
[WINTER TRILLING]

06:16.297 --> 06:17.696
That means she likes you.

06:18.432 --> 06:20.559
Well, imagine my delight.

06:24.371 --> 06:28.740
Not much different from us, really.
Same vertebral structure.

06:28.909 --> 06:32.811
But their skin is hypersensitive. She
might not tolerate anything against it at all.

06:33.013 --> 06:34.446
That's the first step then.

06:34.615 --> 06:36.082
You're doing okay.

06:36.917 --> 06:38.544
Nice and tight.

06:44.325 --> 06:46.953
There's too much power
for what you're proposing to do.

06:47.127 --> 06:49.652
No, there isn't.
We're not gonna be worried about that.

06:49.830 --> 06:53.630
You were talking about the abrasion
part of it. Will you let me finish or what?

06:53.801 --> 06:55.792
[ALL CHATTERING]

07:01.008 --> 07:02.737
[PHONE RINGS]

07:02.910 --> 07:05.811
McCARTHY:
Good idea. Good idea.

07:09.183 --> 07:12.414
[TRILLING]

07:13.120 --> 07:15.850
McCARTHY:
Fine, I think, if this would stay up.

07:16.023 --> 07:17.752
- Like this?
- Ha, ha.

07:18.325 --> 07:21.624
McCARTHY: So this is all gonna be moving
at the same time.

07:21.795 --> 07:24.127
This part is making the tail
kind of go like that.

07:24.298 --> 07:25.526
Exactly.

07:27.635 --> 07:29.626
[TRILLING]

07:30.537 --> 07:32.698
Please understand
that we're strapped for cash.

07:36.543 --> 07:37.567
PHOEBE:
It's amazing.

07:37.745 --> 07:38.837
Amazing. Thank you.

07:39.013 --> 07:40.241
Thank you.

07:40.514 --> 07:42.038
High five.

07:43.350 --> 07:44.715
MAN:
So, what do you need, Cam?

07:44.885 --> 07:47.149
I want you to custom-make some parts
for me.

07:47.321 --> 07:49.380
Not like anything we've done before.

07:49.556 --> 07:50.716
It may not work...

07:50.891 --> 07:52.882
...and I can't pay you.

07:53.060 --> 07:56.461
Other than that, I should be excited, right?
Ha-ha-ha.

07:57.231 --> 07:58.289
Who's the patient?

08:28.762 --> 08:29.854
Bad news?

08:33.701 --> 08:37.193
- Doesn't matter.
- Hmm.

08:39.073 --> 08:40.836
How's the brace holding up?

08:41.008 --> 08:42.475
It's fine.

08:51.251 --> 08:54.550
- What am I supposed to do with that?
- Kick it.

08:54.788 --> 08:56.016
Hard as you can.

08:58.525 --> 09:00.356
Oh, don't worry about breaking
anything.

09:00.527 --> 09:02.085
I own savings bonds.

09:02.262 --> 09:05.288
Something breaks, the government just
buys more. I make money.

09:05.966 --> 09:08.059
I don't think that's how
savings bonds work.

09:08.535 --> 09:10.059
Probably not.

09:10.637 --> 09:12.400
Kick it anyway.

09:28.255 --> 09:29.552
I can't.

09:30.424 --> 09:35.361
Hmm.
Tell me, what hurts more?

09:35.562 --> 09:37.086
Your leg or your pride?

09:43.137 --> 09:46.163
My whole life,
all I wanted to do was one thing.

09:46.607 --> 09:49.633
Well, now you're just gonna have to
want to do something else.

09:50.410 --> 09:53.607
Fortunately, there are about
a million things to choose from.

09:54.815 --> 09:59.684
Look, Kyle, just because you're hurt
doesn't mean you're broken.

09:59.853 --> 10:02.151
No, trust me, I'm broken.

10:03.190 --> 10:04.748
No.

10:09.363 --> 10:10.796
That's broken.

10:14.501 --> 10:16.196
Go home, Kyle.

10:17.838 --> 10:19.829
Go home to your family.

10:22.376 --> 10:27.143
Now, this is the same stuff we use
for humans. It'll protect the skin.

10:27.314 --> 10:31.182
You just slide it right over the stump
and we'll put the prosthetic right over that.

10:31.351 --> 10:35.685
This is something I cooked up
from parts from an old Buick.

10:36.156 --> 10:39.523
It's a little stiff, but it should work
until the real parts are made.

10:41.428 --> 10:43.362
PHOEBE:
Okay, I got her.

10:43.897 --> 10:45.558
- Let's try it.
CLAY: There you go.

10:45.732 --> 10:47.529
All right, hang on, Winter.

10:47.701 --> 10:49.328
[WINTER CLICKING]

10:50.537 --> 10:51.629
[SAWYER WHISTLES]

10:51.805 --> 10:53.500
As tight as you can get it.

10:53.907 --> 10:55.374
SAWYER:
No, no, it's okay.

10:55.542 --> 10:56.566
[WINTER TRILLING]

10:56.743 --> 10:58.904
CLAY: Shh, shh, shh.
PHOEBE: It's okay, Winter.

10:59.079 --> 11:01.377
CLAY:
Pheebs, let's get these straps.

11:01.949 --> 11:02.973
PHOEBE:
Is it tight enough?

11:03.851 --> 11:05.341
CLAY:
It's on.

11:05.519 --> 11:07.009
Okay.

11:07.421 --> 11:09.719
- Back her up.
PHOEBE: Let's go.

11:10.891 --> 11:12.290
[WINTER CLICKING]

11:12.492 --> 11:13.720
Come on, fish.

11:15.696 --> 11:17.994
Go ahead and give her some signals,
Pheebs.

11:19.366 --> 11:21.197
PHOEBE:
It's okay, it's okay.

11:21.935 --> 11:23.664
SAWYER: It's okay.
PHOEBE: It's okay, Winter.

11:24.104 --> 11:25.731
Tail up. Tail down.

11:25.906 --> 11:27.339
SAWYER:
You got this.

11:27.708 --> 11:29.505
PHOEBE:
Tail up. Tail down.

11:31.612 --> 11:33.102
Up and down.

11:33.280 --> 11:35.544
No, Winter. Up and down.

11:35.716 --> 11:36.944
No, Winter.

11:38.418 --> 11:40.045
She doesn't like it.

11:40.554 --> 11:42.579
[CLICKING]

11:44.458 --> 11:46.483
- Winter. Winter.
- Get it off her.

11:46.660 --> 11:48.059
[WINTER SQUEALING]

11:48.228 --> 11:49.252
I can't do anything.

11:49.429 --> 11:50.953
Dad, you gotta make her stop.

11:51.131 --> 11:53.599
PHOEBE: Winter, no. Stop.
HAZEL: Dad, do something.

11:54.468 --> 11:56.095
PHOEBE: Winter.
- Dad.

11:57.137 --> 11:58.536
[WINTER SQUEALS]

12:10.717 --> 12:12.708
[WINTER TRILLING]

12:21.328 --> 12:23.091
SANDRA [OVER TV]:
<i>Thanks, Jerry. This just in:</i>

12:23.263 --> 12:26.664
<i>Tropical Storm Leroy, now churning</i>
<i>across the Gulf of Mexico...</i>

12:26.833 --> 12:29.393
<i>...with winds of up to 80 miles an hour...</i>
- Phoebe.

12:29.569 --> 12:32.697
<i>... has just been upgraded</i>
<i>to a Category One hurricane.</i>

12:32.873 --> 12:37.071
<i>Stay tuned, as we'll bring you</i>
<i>the very latest details as they come in.</i>

12:38.412 --> 12:40.209
CLAY: Phoebe, help me here, please.
PHOEBE: Okay.

12:40.380 --> 12:41.904
- Okay, I got it.
CLAY: You got it?

12:42.082 --> 12:43.106
PHOEBE:
Yeah, let's go.

12:43.283 --> 12:45.478
CLAY: Hey, guys,
I need all of this stuff downstairs.

12:45.652 --> 12:47.483
Everything goes downstairs.

12:47.955 --> 12:49.946
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

12:57.064 --> 12:59.055
[WIND HOWLING]

13:08.575 --> 13:09.599
CLAY:
Sawyer.

13:09.776 --> 13:11.869
Sawyer, your mom's here.
You gotta go home.

13:12.045 --> 13:14.809
- What about the animals?
- Don't worry about them. Go home.

13:14.982 --> 13:17.348
Kat, you go too. Go.

13:19.653 --> 13:21.518
Come on, let's get in our spot.

13:33.633 --> 13:35.100
Hi, Mom.

13:38.238 --> 13:40.263
No, no, no, I got it, son.

13:42.509 --> 13:43.533
CLAY:
<i>Come on, Phoebe.</i>

13:43.710 --> 13:45.075
We gotta get inside.

13:45.245 --> 13:47.076
PHOEBE:
Okay. Good girls.

13:47.280 --> 13:49.305
[TRILLS]

13:51.752 --> 13:53.117
CLAY:
Hazel.

13:54.855 --> 13:56.880
HAZEL:
Dad. Here I am.

14:10.904 --> 14:12.337
Mom?

14:12.506 --> 14:14.030
It's okay, honey.

14:15.208 --> 14:18.939
It's just a big old storm. We'll be okay.

14:35.529 --> 14:37.554
[RUFUS SQUAWKING]

14:38.231 --> 14:39.721
HAZEL:
He's scared.

14:50.777 --> 14:52.768
[WATER TRICKLING]

15:35.989 --> 15:37.980
[MACHINE WHIRRING]

15:41.294 --> 15:44.229
CLAY: Hey, when you're finished up there,
come on down, will you?

15:44.397 --> 15:47.264
Got some other things
I need your help with.

15:52.005 --> 15:53.302
Kyle.

15:55.075 --> 15:56.804
Figured you could use a hand.

16:00.714 --> 16:02.807
And maybe one good leg.

16:03.216 --> 16:06.617
Hey, Dr. Clay, Hazel, Reed.
This is my cousin Kyle.

16:06.786 --> 16:07.912
And my Aunt Alyce.

16:08.088 --> 16:10.147
- Hey, how you doing? Nice to meet you.
KYLE: Hi.

16:25.805 --> 16:27.796
[WINTER CLICKING]

16:30.610 --> 16:34.307
It's okay. I can do this.

16:42.989 --> 16:44.388
Ah, ahh...

16:48.828 --> 16:50.557
Hold your hand out.

16:51.765 --> 16:53.790
[WINTER CLICKING]

16:53.967 --> 16:55.525
Come on.

16:58.738 --> 17:00.228
[TRILLING]

17:09.281 --> 17:10.407
[CHUCKLES]

17:21.194 --> 17:23.185
GLORIA:
The best guess is what?

17:23.363 --> 17:25.387
Including structural damage...

17:25.598 --> 17:29.330
...the truck, rescue equipment,
electrical systems...

17:29.502 --> 17:31.868
...something in the range of 500,000.

17:35.108 --> 17:36.598
So this is it.

17:37.177 --> 17:41.807
Gloria, I really feel like we've exhausted
all of our options here.

17:43.383 --> 17:46.147
So we're all in agreement, then.

17:47.254 --> 17:49.188
We go ahead with the sale?

17:51.258 --> 17:52.987
In favor?

17:59.933 --> 18:02.458
I'll call Mr. Hordern and tell him.

18:02.836 --> 18:06.169
We found homes for all the fish
and the animals.

18:06.339 --> 18:07.670
Including Winter?

18:08.241 --> 18:09.265
[SIGHS]

18:09.442 --> 18:10.466
Clay...

18:10.644 --> 18:15.604
The plain truth is no one wants
an animal with her disability.

18:15.882 --> 18:20.410
No dolphin has ever been known
to lose its entire tail and survive.

18:20.587 --> 18:23.283
Every aquarium in the country
says it's hopeless.

18:23.723 --> 18:25.714
Well, they haven't met Winter.

18:26.559 --> 18:30.427
Listen, Dr. McCarthy is looking into
some new materials, right?

18:30.597 --> 18:32.792
He says he can have
a new tail ready by...

18:32.966 --> 18:34.661
What if she rejects that one too?

18:34.834 --> 18:37.462
She won't. Two weeks.
Just give me two weeks.

18:37.637 --> 18:38.831
I can't.

18:39.272 --> 18:40.967
There is no money.

18:42.442 --> 18:45.468
We have to start thinking
about putting Winter down.

18:47.047 --> 18:49.641
It's the kindest thing we can do.

18:55.155 --> 18:57.248
- No.
- I don't have a choice.

18:57.424 --> 18:59.722
Of course you do.
Dr. McCarthy said we only need...

18:59.893 --> 19:01.724
Dr. McCarthy stopped work.

19:02.128 --> 19:03.152
I asked him to.

19:05.332 --> 19:06.822
Why?

19:07.701 --> 19:09.100
[SIGHS]

19:12.172 --> 19:13.469
Come over here.

19:18.478 --> 19:19.877
I'm out of time.

19:21.848 --> 19:23.611
I'm out of money.

19:25.418 --> 19:26.976
I have to close down.

19:28.621 --> 19:31.249
Dad, how could you let this happen?

19:31.491 --> 19:33.686
I don't keep secrets from you, Hazel.

19:33.860 --> 19:35.589
I never have.

19:36.496 --> 19:38.987
I'm telling you kids this because I think...

19:41.167 --> 19:44.466
Because I think it's time
you start saying your goodbyes.

19:46.339 --> 19:47.601
[SOBS]

20:10.497 --> 20:12.226
[CAR DOOR OPENS]

20:12.999 --> 20:16.457
Excuse me.
Is this the Clearwater Marine Hospital?

20:17.137 --> 20:20.038
Oh, yeah. Sorry, our sign blew down.

20:20.573 --> 20:23.064
Thank you. We drove all the way down
from Atlanta.

20:23.243 --> 20:25.905
If y'all were closed,
I don't know what I would have done.

20:26.413 --> 20:29.871
- We've come to see the dolphin.
- Her name's Winter, Mommy.

20:30.049 --> 20:33.041
Her cousin was here with a school group
and told us about her...

20:33.219 --> 20:36.120
...and ever since then,
it's all my daughter talks about.

20:36.289 --> 20:38.917
After the storm,
we went online to see if she was okay...

20:39.092 --> 20:40.616
...but we couldn't find anything.

20:41.027 --> 20:43.791
She's fine. All the animals are.

20:45.098 --> 20:47.896
You think it'd be okay
if we just had a little peek?

20:50.503 --> 20:51.595
Sure, I guess.

20:51.771 --> 20:53.170
Thanks.

21:08.588 --> 21:09.919
Hi.

21:11.224 --> 21:12.657
Hi.

21:22.969 --> 21:24.231
Wow.

21:25.104 --> 21:27.197
Oh, my goodness.

21:28.074 --> 21:31.168
Look at that huge skeleton.

21:31.377 --> 21:33.470
- Wow.
- Wow.

21:33.646 --> 21:35.511
Oh, look up there.

21:35.682 --> 21:37.047
You see it?

21:37.450 --> 21:38.712
Come over here, guys.

21:48.495 --> 21:49.860
MOM:
Wow.

21:51.231 --> 21:52.357
It's cool, huh?

21:53.233 --> 21:54.928
Where's Winter?

21:57.470 --> 21:59.028
Just wait a sec.

22:22.262 --> 22:24.992
Mommy, she's just like me.

22:30.036 --> 22:33.164
But you said there wasn't a solution.
This is a solution.

22:33.339 --> 22:34.772
CLAY: You don't understand...
SAWYER: I do.

22:34.941 --> 22:38.570
You need money. I get that.
But Winter can raise a lot of money.

22:38.745 --> 22:41.077
That lady drove eight hours
to bring her daughter here.

22:41.247 --> 22:43.044
And other people would do that too.

22:43.216 --> 22:44.808
- We need a website.
- With a webcam.

22:44.984 --> 22:46.576
SAWYER: Make donations.
HAZEL: A big carnival.

22:46.753 --> 22:48.311
Everybody could see her new tail.

22:48.488 --> 22:52.185
Guys, I'm really proud of you.

22:53.159 --> 22:55.184
I love the ideas...

22:56.129 --> 22:58.563
...but they're just not realistic,
you know?

23:01.067 --> 23:05.026
It wasn't realistic to save Winter
in the first place, but you did it.

23:06.239 --> 23:09.731
I am really sorry, guys. I really am.

23:10.743 --> 23:12.210
It just wouldn't be enough.

23:24.657 --> 23:27.592
Remember that poem I used to read you
when you were little?

23:28.828 --> 23:33.697
<i>I must down to the seas again</i>
<i>To the lonely sea and sky</i>

23:34.834 --> 23:38.292
<i>And all I ask is a tall ship</i>

23:38.605 --> 23:41.335
<i>And a star to steer her by</i>

23:43.343 --> 23:45.709
You're a good sailor, Clay.

23:46.212 --> 23:50.444
You know the sea and sky
better than any man I ever met.

23:51.684 --> 23:53.982
But you are sorely lost now, son.

23:55.888 --> 23:57.583
You're giving up.

23:58.625 --> 24:00.923
Because you're afraid you can't save her.

24:03.363 --> 24:05.957
And you don't want to watch that
happen again.

24:07.900 --> 24:09.094
Well...

24:10.003 --> 24:12.028
...Winter might die.

24:13.506 --> 24:15.133
I don't know.

24:16.075 --> 24:19.977
But I do know you can't give up on her.

24:21.948 --> 24:24.246
You never did on Holly.

24:24.550 --> 24:29.112
It was the bravest, most beautiful thing
I ever saw.

24:30.390 --> 24:33.587
Just because we haven't got
to where the star's pointing us...

24:33.760 --> 24:35.694
...doesn't make it the wrong star.

24:37.630 --> 24:40.463
That dolphin's taking us all somewhere.

24:41.834 --> 24:44.598
We just haven't figured out where yet.

24:48.574 --> 24:50.041
Sawyer?

24:53.946 --> 24:58.212
So you want to talk me through
this fundraising stuff again?

25:01.487 --> 25:04.422
Okay, you're gonna help me with
the baking and food committee.

25:04.590 --> 25:06.455
I need you
on the decorations committee.

25:06.626 --> 25:08.116
Yeah, Gloria, I know. Ha, ha.

25:08.294 --> 25:11.627
I know it sounds crazy.
I need you to stall him.

25:11.798 --> 25:12.958
As long as you can.

25:13.132 --> 25:17.296
It's a big benefit for the Marine Hospital.
We're calling it "Save Winter Day."

25:17.704 --> 25:19.433
You can? Great.

25:19.605 --> 25:20.697
- Hey.
- Hey.

25:20.873 --> 25:23.671
This is quite the operation
you got going on here, huh?

25:23.843 --> 25:26.368
Yeah. I just hope we can
sell enough tickets.

25:26.546 --> 25:28.173
[PHONE RINGS]

25:28.347 --> 25:29.609
Dr. McCarthy?

25:29.782 --> 25:31.613
Thank you so much for calling me back.

25:31.784 --> 25:33.843
I just wanted to make sure that...

25:35.922 --> 25:38.413
MAN: Have a good weekend, Sandra.
SANDRA: Thanks.

25:43.896 --> 25:45.227
So...

25:46.065 --> 25:48.625
I wondered if I could ask you a favor.

25:49.268 --> 25:50.292
Sure.

25:50.470 --> 25:51.869
[WINTER TRILLING]

25:52.205 --> 25:53.638
Okay, move it to the left.

25:54.006 --> 25:56.270
Farther, farther.

25:56.442 --> 25:58.069
Okay.

26:01.614 --> 26:03.206
Okay, slide it out more.

26:04.050 --> 26:05.108
More.

26:05.284 --> 26:06.581
A little more.

26:07.253 --> 26:08.379
Little more.

26:10.056 --> 26:11.921
- Uh-oh.
- Ah!

26:13.860 --> 26:15.088
Never mind.

26:15.261 --> 26:17.126
SAWYER:
Maybe we should make it a little bigger.

26:17.296 --> 26:19.560
Hey, guys.
You might want to come see this.

26:20.500 --> 26:22.263
- See what?
KYLE: It's a surprise.

26:22.435 --> 26:23.834
SANDRA [OVER TV]:
<i>Thanks, Jerry.</i>

26:24.003 --> 26:28.906
<i>Just months ago, little Winter was found</i>
<i>tangled in the ropes of a crab trap.</i>

26:29.075 --> 26:30.736
<i>Her tail seriously damaged.</i>

26:30.910 --> 26:34.641
<i>Rushed to Clearwater Marine Hospital,</i>
<i>it appeared she might not survive.</i>

26:34.814 --> 26:38.181
<i>But the plucky animal did,</i>
<i>although her tail did not.</i>

26:38.351 --> 26:40.512
<i>And without a tail, how could she swim?</i>

26:40.920 --> 26:44.822
<i>Well, she taught herself to</i>
<i>with a wiggling motion, side to side.</i>

26:44.991 --> 26:47.289
<i>But it's not a happy ending yet.</i>

26:47.760 --> 26:51.025
<i>That unusual swimming motion</i>
<i>is damaging her spine...</i>

26:51.197 --> 26:53.188
<i>... which could lead to paralysis.</i>

26:53.366 --> 26:56.358
<i>The solution? Make her a prosthetic tail.</i>

26:56.536 --> 26:59.835
<i>And with the help of prosthetic designer</i>
<i>Dr. Cameron McCarthy...</i>

27:00.006 --> 27:01.803
<i>... they're doing just that.</i>

27:01.974 --> 27:03.703
<i>But it will take time and money.</i>

27:04.110 --> 27:07.045
<i>So Winter's best friend,</i>
<i>11-year-old Sawyer Nelson...</i>

27:07.213 --> 27:10.376
<i>... has created a website,</i>
<i>SeeWinter.com...</i>

27:10.550 --> 27:14.042
<i>... with a live webcam where you can</i>
<i>log on and meet her for yourself.</i>

27:14.220 --> 27:19.214
<i>Or better yet, meet her in person on</i>
<i>Save Winter Day, Saturday the 27th.</i>

27:19.392 --> 27:21.792
<i>And, as an added bonus...</i>

27:21.961 --> 27:24.429
<i>... you'll be treated to a very special</i>
<i>sporting event.</i>

27:24.597 --> 27:26.360
<i>Two of America's top young swimmers...</i>

27:26.532 --> 27:28.659
<i>... Florida's Kyle Connellan</i>
<i>and Donovan Peck...</i>

27:28.835 --> 27:31.065
<i>...have agreed to race head-to-head...</i>
- Really?

27:31.237 --> 27:34.638
<i>... with all proceeds going to benefit</i>
<i>Winter and the Marine Hospital.</i>

27:34.807 --> 27:36.206
<i>So come and meet two...</i>

27:36.375 --> 27:39.242
<i>... of our finest athletes</i>
<i>and one heroic little dolphin.</i>

27:39.412 --> 27:44.076
<i>I guarantee she'll steal your heart,</i>
<i>just like she did mine.</i>

27:46.018 --> 27:47.645
SAWYER:
All right, a little more.

27:48.254 --> 27:49.744
Farther.

27:50.356 --> 27:52.017
All right, down.

27:53.192 --> 27:54.659
WOMAN:
All right.

27:55.328 --> 27:57.956
Sawyer. Sawyer. He's here.

27:58.297 --> 28:00.663
- Good work, guys.
- Come on.

28:00.833 --> 28:03.734
McCARTHY: <i>All right. Cross your fingers</i>
<i>and toes if you got them.</i>

28:04.403 --> 28:05.427
[HAZEL GASPS]

28:05.605 --> 28:07.266
HAZEL:
Oh, it's beautiful.

28:07.440 --> 28:10.034
McCARTHY:
Yeah, the joints are a little more flexible.

28:10.243 --> 28:13.007
So it should feel more natural. Hmm?

28:15.248 --> 28:17.182
[WINTER TRILLING]

28:17.350 --> 28:18.510
CLAY:
Here you go.

28:19.118 --> 28:20.847
PHOEBE:
Can we show this to her?

28:21.020 --> 28:22.681
SAWYER:
It's okay.

28:24.123 --> 28:25.351
You okay?

28:26.292 --> 28:29.125
PHOEBE:
Hold it in front of her eye. Let her see it.

28:30.596 --> 28:31.961
KAT:
Here.

28:33.132 --> 28:34.963
You ready?

28:35.134 --> 28:37.261
PHOEBE: Okay, let's do this.
SAWYER: Good girl.

28:39.171 --> 28:40.502
Come on.

28:41.707 --> 28:43.038
CLAY:
I got it.

28:45.177 --> 28:50.046
McCARTHY: Clay? Make sure you snug it
right up close to the stump. Real close.

28:50.216 --> 28:51.683
CLAY:
Okay.

28:54.320 --> 28:55.378
PHOEBE:
You got it?

28:56.522 --> 28:58.854
CLAY:
Well, it fits, that's for sure.

28:59.025 --> 29:01.289
That's about as snug as I can get it.
Can you see?

29:01.994 --> 29:04.758
Just try to get her attention, Phoebe.

29:06.332 --> 29:09.426
PHOEBE: You can do it. Up and down.
Up and down.

29:09.602 --> 29:11.001
Good girl.

29:11.704 --> 29:13.729
Up and down, Winter. Up and down.

29:14.040 --> 29:16.406
Up and down. Up and down.

29:16.575 --> 29:18.805
[WINTER TRILLING]

29:19.011 --> 29:20.638
You ready?

29:20.813 --> 29:22.940
All right, let's do this, Winter.

29:23.249 --> 29:25.376
PHOEBE:
She's good. Keep her steady.

29:27.687 --> 29:29.245
Good job.

29:32.758 --> 29:34.589
You can do it.

29:34.760 --> 29:36.557
Oh, lookie there.

29:45.705 --> 29:46.967
Winter.

29:47.406 --> 29:48.964
Winter, no.

29:50.576 --> 29:51.600
[WINTER SQUEALING]

29:51.777 --> 29:53.005
Winter, stop.

30:15.234 --> 30:16.724
Hey, Mom.

30:18.404 --> 30:21.532
I'm sure you're busy
with lots of other stuff.

30:22.274 --> 30:26.438
But if there's anything you can do
to help Winter and her tail...

30:27.179 --> 30:29.340
...we'd all really appreciate it.

30:37.923 --> 30:39.914
[WINTER TRILLING]

30:40.659 --> 30:43.526
Winter, no. Just stop.

30:46.098 --> 30:48.828
Winter, no.
I don't want to play right now.

30:52.505 --> 30:53.836
You don't understand, do you?

30:55.808 --> 30:58.504
I thought dolphins
were supposed to be smart.

31:03.616 --> 31:05.550
Why won't you understand?

31:10.456 --> 31:12.048
Don't you get it?

31:12.224 --> 31:14.920
If you don't wear the tail,
you're gonna die.

31:19.131 --> 31:21.361
Why won't you just wear the tail?

31:26.105 --> 31:27.470
[WINTER GRUNTS]

31:33.946 --> 31:35.937
[WINTER CLICKING]

31:36.415 --> 31:37.882
Winter, what are you doing?

31:38.050 --> 31:39.039
[TRILLING]

31:40.753 --> 31:43.654
Hey, cut it out. I don't want to play.

31:50.596 --> 31:52.154
Dr. Clay.

31:52.965 --> 31:54.489
Dr. Clay.

31:54.667 --> 31:56.157
Dr. Clay.

31:57.203 --> 31:59.034
- I know what it is now.
- What?

31:59.205 --> 32:01.765
It's not the tail, it's the sock.
It's like a seat belt.

32:01.941 --> 32:03.169
Wait a minute. What?

32:03.342 --> 32:06.743
No, no. When it rubs.
It's not the tail we have to fix, it's the sock.

32:17.590 --> 32:19.683
MAN:
Okay, Sandra, we're live.

32:19.859 --> 32:23.989
Five, four, three, two...

32:24.163 --> 32:26.256
SANDRA:
I'm Sandra Sinclair with Bay News 9...

32:26.432 --> 32:29.492
...here at Clearwater Marine Hospital
for Save Winter Day.

32:29.668 --> 32:30.726
COACH:
How you doing?

32:30.903 --> 32:32.894
- How you doing, coach?
- Good. You look good.

32:33.072 --> 32:35.666
- Thanks for being here.
- Man, I wouldn't have missed it.

32:36.308 --> 32:40.677
I'll be darned if I'm gonna tell anyone this
whole thing was organized by 11-year-olds.

32:40.846 --> 32:42.108
[CHUCKLING]

32:44.216 --> 32:46.446
Thank you. That's very generous.

32:46.952 --> 32:49.546
Well, let's just say that Winter and I
are old friends.

32:49.722 --> 32:51.189
[CHUCKLES]

32:54.727 --> 32:56.752
Hey, Kat, have you seen Dr. McCarthy?

32:56.929 --> 32:58.556
No, not yet.

32:59.365 --> 33:02.493
[RUFUS SQUAWKING]
[DOYLE MUTTERING]

33:02.668 --> 33:04.397
Go away. Please.

33:04.570 --> 33:05.867
Good grief.

33:06.038 --> 33:07.232
LORRAINE:
Hey, Mr. Doyle.

33:07.406 --> 33:08.566
Oh. Oh, hi. Um...

33:08.741 --> 33:09.969
Hi.

33:10.142 --> 33:13.839
I read Sawyer's essay...

33:14.513 --> 33:16.003
Ha! It's quite good, actually.

33:16.182 --> 33:21.210
And considering everything
that he has done here, I figured that...

33:22.555 --> 33:25.490
...I could get him credit
for summer school.

33:26.358 --> 33:29.020
Considering that news,
I'll call off the pelican.

33:29.195 --> 33:31.220
Shoo, Rufus. Go on.

33:31.864 --> 33:35.322
- Have a wonderful afternoon, Mr. Doyle.
McCARTHY: Beep-beep-beep-beep.

33:35.501 --> 33:37.526
Beep-beep. Hoo-gah. Hoo-hoo-hoogah.

33:37.703 --> 33:38.965
Excuse me. Bye-bye.

33:39.138 --> 33:41.106
Excuse me, excuse me. Excuse me.

33:41.273 --> 33:42.706
Dr. McCarthy.

33:42.875 --> 33:44.103
What a mob.

33:44.510 --> 33:45.772
- Is it done?
- Is it ready?

33:45.945 --> 33:48.072
Can't a man catch
his breath for a minute...

33:48.247 --> 33:50.807
...before you start bombarding him
with questions?

33:51.483 --> 33:52.609
It's in here.

33:52.785 --> 33:53.911
SAWYER:
Yes.

33:56.155 --> 33:59.556
I must've tried 20 different formulas,
but I think we got something.

34:01.293 --> 34:02.954
It's a silicone elastomer.

34:03.128 --> 34:05.892
Saltwater-proof. Extra sticky.

34:06.098 --> 34:08.532
- And softer than a lamb's bottom.
SAWYER & HAZEL: Wow.

34:09.034 --> 34:10.626
McCARTHY:
I call it "Winter's gel."

34:10.803 --> 34:13.203
I'll tell you what:
If the fish doesn't like it...

34:13.371 --> 34:16.101
...I'm putting the tail on
and swimming with it myself.

34:16.275 --> 34:17.333
JOHN:
Gloria.

34:17.509 --> 34:19.136
Wait up.

34:20.246 --> 34:22.304
All right, thanks very much.

34:23.849 --> 34:24.907
That was the lawyer.

34:25.083 --> 34:27.882
The deal's closed.
It all belongs to Hordern now.

34:29.855 --> 34:33.621
Gloria, a bake sale wouldn't fix this.
We did the right thing.

34:34.927 --> 34:35.951
Did we?

34:36.862 --> 34:38.795
I'm not so sure.

34:40.666 --> 34:41.826
Not too tight?

34:42.001 --> 34:43.592
I don't think so.

34:44.436 --> 34:46.495
SAWYER:
It's okay, it's okay. Shh, shh, shh.

34:46.672 --> 34:48.639
Attagirl. Attagirl.

34:48.806 --> 34:50.434
CLAY: You got it, Pheebs?
- I got it.

34:50.609 --> 34:51.735
All right, it's on.

34:52.777 --> 34:55.338
PHOEBE: Does that feel better?
Does that feel good?

34:59.785 --> 35:01.650
CLAY:
All right, just give her a second.

35:08.494 --> 35:09.518
[TRILLING]

35:09.695 --> 35:11.595
CLAY:
Give her the signals, Pheeb.

35:11.764 --> 35:13.561
Can you lift it, just a little bit?

35:13.732 --> 35:15.996
Up and down, Winter. Up and down.

35:16.535 --> 35:21.199
Good girl. Good girl. I know. Okay.

35:21.373 --> 35:22.431
Let's try this, okay?

35:23.942 --> 35:25.500
Come on.

35:30.249 --> 35:31.273
Come on.

35:31.750 --> 35:33.047
Come on, girl. Come on.

35:38.891 --> 35:39.949
Come on, Winter.

35:41.994 --> 35:43.393
No.

35:45.030 --> 35:46.657
- No, Winter.
- Come on, Winter.

36:06.819 --> 36:08.980
Good girl, Winter. Up and down.

36:11.657 --> 36:12.919
She's doing it.

36:22.234 --> 36:23.701
She's doing it.

36:30.843 --> 36:32.105
She's swimming.

36:34.113 --> 36:35.205
She's doing it.

36:35.381 --> 36:36.939
[CLAY LAUGHS]

36:39.351 --> 36:43.845
- Go, Winter.
- Swim, you stupid fish. Swim.

36:50.529 --> 36:52.520
[TRILLING]

36:54.133 --> 36:55.862
[LAUGHS]

37:04.309 --> 37:08.712
Good girl. Good girl, Winter.
Yes, yes, you did it.

37:08.881 --> 37:10.746
- Good girl.
- You did it.

37:13.886 --> 37:14.910
I know.

37:21.360 --> 37:23.726
Hey, guys. Everything ready?

37:24.530 --> 37:25.554
Yeah.

37:26.698 --> 37:28.666
All right, now, listen.

37:28.834 --> 37:33.271
No matter what happens,
today belongs to you two.

37:33.839 --> 37:37.468
You never quit on Winter
and you never quit on yourselves.

37:38.844 --> 37:40.812
You'll always have that.

37:50.923 --> 37:52.288
Hello.

37:52.458 --> 37:54.585
I'm Clay Haskett.

37:55.327 --> 37:58.262
Welcome to the Clearwater
Marine Hospital.

37:58.430 --> 38:00.421
[CROWD CHEERING]

38:04.203 --> 38:07.297
I'm so thrilled
that everyone could come today.

38:08.106 --> 38:13.305
I'd also like to introduce
two very special guests.

38:13.479 --> 38:16.937
First, state swimming champion
Donovan Peck.

38:17.115 --> 38:18.980
[CROWD CHEERING]

38:19.151 --> 38:20.618
Donovan.

38:26.992 --> 38:29.324
And Private Kyle Connellan.

38:29.495 --> 38:31.156
[CROWD CHEERING]

38:37.569 --> 38:40.060
- Whoo!
WOMAN: Kyle!

38:48.580 --> 38:49.877
So proud of him.

38:51.116 --> 38:52.674
[HAZEL SQUEALS]

38:53.385 --> 38:55.216
Yeah, Kyle.

39:03.829 --> 39:05.262
KYLE:
Thank you.

39:06.598 --> 39:07.758
Thank you very much...

39:08.333 --> 39:10.995
...but I'm not the reason
we're all here today.

39:12.704 --> 39:13.728
Come on, Sawyer.

39:16.909 --> 39:18.672
Go. Go.

39:20.312 --> 39:23.577
Ladies and gentlemen, my cousin...

39:24.283 --> 39:25.614
...Sawyer Nelson.

39:25.784 --> 39:27.775
[CROWD CHEERING]

39:34.293 --> 39:35.726
Sawyer.

39:35.894 --> 39:37.589
[LAUGHING]

39:43.468 --> 39:44.696
[FEEDBACK SQUEALS]

39:44.870 --> 39:48.237
Wow. I don't know what to say.

39:50.142 --> 39:52.076
But I do know...

39:52.844 --> 39:54.744
...it wasn't me
that made this day happen.

39:56.515 --> 40:01.248
We're here because of the most amazing
animal, and friend, that I've ever known.

40:02.087 --> 40:04.453
And I hope you love her as much as I do.

40:05.757 --> 40:07.748
Because Winter and I are family now.

40:12.464 --> 40:14.261
And family is forever.

40:15.000 --> 40:16.991
[CROWD CHEERING]

40:35.120 --> 40:36.280
All right. You good?

40:36.488 --> 40:37.819
Yeah.

40:38.523 --> 40:42.220
All right, 400 meters out,
around the buoy and back.

40:42.394 --> 40:44.021
- You got it?
- Uh-huh.

40:45.764 --> 40:48.255
Now, I may not be able to kick so well...

40:48.433 --> 40:51.095
...but don't you dare take it easy on me,
all right?

40:51.269 --> 40:52.600
COACH:
Okay, guys, take your mark.

40:54.139 --> 40:55.333
And by the way...

40:55.574 --> 40:57.906
...did I forget to mention
this is a relay race?

40:58.076 --> 40:59.270
DONOVAN:
What?

41:02.214 --> 41:03.909
HAZEL:
Come on, Kyle.

41:06.318 --> 41:07.649
[HAZEL SQUEALS]

41:12.891 --> 41:14.415
- Whoo!
- Whoo!

41:15.594 --> 41:16.856
Come on.

41:22.701 --> 41:24.896
MAN: Where's he going?
- What?

41:41.687 --> 41:43.678
[CROWD CHEERING]

41:44.856 --> 41:47.051
SANDRA:
Oh, look. Guys, I think that's Winter.

41:50.262 --> 41:51.627
Phoebe.

41:52.431 --> 41:54.058
PHOEBE:
Careful.

41:55.667 --> 41:57.294
Go, Winter.

41:57.669 --> 42:00.263
KAT: Go, Winter.
PHOEBE: Whoo-hoo!

42:09.181 --> 42:12.207
Let's go. Come on.
You can do better than that.

42:16.188 --> 42:18.588
Now it's a fair fight.
There you go. Come on.

42:18.890 --> 42:21.017
[WINTER TRILLING]

42:24.396 --> 42:25.693
[CROWD CHEERING]

42:27.899 --> 42:29.423
Yeah, there you go, Winter.

42:32.170 --> 42:33.967
I think she's getting the hang of it.

42:34.139 --> 42:35.436
- I think you're right.
- Whoo!

42:38.543 --> 42:40.704
Thanks, buddy. Thank you. Whoa!

42:43.849 --> 42:46.909
- Come on, Winter. Whoo!
- Good girl.

42:47.419 --> 42:48.784
Whoa!

42:52.791 --> 42:53.985
[HAZEL SQUEALS]

42:56.261 --> 42:57.592
BOY:
Come on.

42:57.763 --> 42:59.754
[CHILDREN YELLING]

43:15.113 --> 43:18.207
Man, I gotta tell you,
I didn't see that coming. Ha, ha.

43:18.383 --> 43:20.248
- A little help?
- Nice job.

43:20.418 --> 43:21.476
- Doing all right?
KYLE: Yeah.

43:21.653 --> 43:23.621
Good girl, Winter. Good girl.

43:24.523 --> 43:26.218
- Ah.
- Hey, doc.

43:26.391 --> 43:27.585
Thanks for everything.

43:27.759 --> 43:29.590
It's been my great pleasure, Kyle.

43:29.761 --> 43:31.422
Clay.

43:31.696 --> 43:32.958
Oh, hey, Gloria.

43:33.665 --> 43:35.292
I'd say she's a hit.

43:35.467 --> 43:37.526
Ha, ha. I think so.

43:37.702 --> 43:38.964
Dr. Haskett.

43:40.672 --> 43:41.832
Phil Hordern.

43:42.274 --> 43:45.801
I just wanted to tell you all how excited
I am about buying this place.

43:46.912 --> 43:48.277
So it's official.

43:48.446 --> 43:50.175
Yes, sir, it is.

